Developers On Strike
--------------------

It=E2=80=99s certainly possible that I=E2=80=99m reading too much into thes=
e absences: maybe these three companies simply didn=E2=80=99t get enough Vi=
sions Pro to build a native app, and felt uncomfortable releasing their iPa=
d versions without knowing how useful they would be. YouTube in particular,=
 given that much of its usage is free, likely has less of a beef with Apple=
 than Netflix or Spotify do, and it=E2=80=99s easy enough to believe that G=
oogle just isn=E2=80=99t a company that moves that fast these days.

Still, there=E2=80=99s no question that the biggest beneficiary of these co=
mpanies being on the Vision Pro =E2=80=94 and, correspondingly, the biggest=
 loser from their absence =E2=80=94 is Apple. The company is launching an a=
udacious and ambitious new product, and there are major partners in its eco=
system that aren=E2=80=99t interested in helping.

This is the consequence of fashioning App Store policies as a stick: until =
there is a carrot of a massive user base, it=E2=80=99s hard to see why deve=
lopers of any size would be particularly motivated to build experiences for=
 the Vision Pro, which will make it that much more difficult to attract sai=
d massive user base. Apple was happy to remind users that, when it came to =
the iPhone, there=E2=80=99s an app for that ( https://www.youtube.com/watch=
?v=3DszrsfeyLzyg ) ; in the case of the Vision Pro, there may not be: this =
is the one and only chance for developers to go on strike without suffering=
 an Epic-like fate, and some of them are taking it.

For now, Apple appears to be so supply-constrained that it doesn=E2=80=99t =
matter; the company will likely sell as many units as it can make. I would =
guess that Apple=E2=80=99s strategy with regards to developer hold-outs wil=
l be to wait them out, trusting that it can sell enough devices that develo=
pers can=E2=80=99t go on strike forever. I certainly think this approach is=
 more likely than offering any sort of concessions to developers, on any of=
 its platforms.

